T1  - Forecasting turning points in international output growth rates using Bayesian exponentially weighted autoregression, time-varying parameter, and pooling techniques
AU  - Zellner, Arnold
AU  - Hong, Chansik
AU  - Min, Chung-ki
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
SP  - 275
EP  - 304
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90016-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407691900167
AB  - In this paper two variants of an autoregressive, leading indicator (ARLI) model are employed to forecast turning points in the growth rates of 18 countries' annual real output for the years 1974–1986. Bayesian predictive densities have been employed to compute probabilities of downturns and upturns, and they have been employed in a Bayesian decision-theoretic framework to obtain optimal turning point forecasts. Various versions of the ARLI model, with and without pooling of data across countries, produced about 70 to 80 percent correct forecasts for 158 turning points. Time-varying parameter models performed slightly better than others. The performance of the ARLI models in forecasting turning points is shown to be considerably better than that of four naive methods of forecasting turning points.
